x4freetext: LANSCE war facility.
The 10B target was 2.5 WNR thick with a 0.05 mm
thick tantalum backing.
Four de e telescope.
The experiment was performed at LANSCE WNR to
investigate the proton channel from the 10B + n
system. This experiment was performed in the NZ
chamber. The experiment was designed to observe
protons up to 20 MeV. The thickness of boron on a
tantalum backing was optimized to give less than 0.5
MeV energy loss for protons of 0.5 MeV traversing the
target layer at 45 degrees, the maximum angle used
here, with respect to the normal. The target was
located 9.12 meters from the neutron source. During
this experiment, a small amount of polyethylene was
placed in the beamline to reduce the low energy
portion of the incident neutron spectrum. Four de e
telescopes at 20, 60, 90, and 135 degrees were used
with gas proportional detectors for the de and a
silicon detector for the e detector. The solid angles
of the detectors were 13.1, 20.4, 26.8 and 16.6 msr,
respectively. The neutron flux was monitored with a
235U fission chamber one meter downstream of the
chamber.
The systematic uncertainties in the
composition of the target, the uranium deposits of
the fission chamber, the efficiency of the fission
chamber, and the detector efficiency can then be
reduced to a single normalization error. The
systematic uncertainties from the fission detector
and the target thickness may be reduced if a
normalization to a higher precision work is made in
the future. There are other uncertainties in the
experiment that are more difficult to quantify. These
include: the choice of the charged-particle gates
used for each reaction channel, the correction of the
neutron time-of-flight, the correction of time shifts
in the fission spectra, and the 235U isotopic
composition.
